<subSubSection id="B14710ACA65414F41B6059EDBDCC0873" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="BA3E723CCA91D8A784DCEBFEC0B94BAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="621F7A58FF329863642C61EF8279FCD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="CB10B787709320390F9802E2AAF09002" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis id="C888C333DCB7603E1313A8235F2F98FA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="156FCFBDFEF259A56C9D90348C8A6C9B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abutiloides">
<emphasis id="D66EA26D26D3D9726E77E3CAB7C48E91" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. abutiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in their liana habit, leaves grey-tomentose or sericeous beneath, their oblong-elliptic sepals and their inflorescences which have a tendency to become leafy and racemose or even paniculate towards the branch tips. They are best distinguished by the sepal indumentum, 
<taxonomicName id="8D94D26E9EBE6F4904019C860286A9A5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis id="7C20D480B7B6C723AC99E87A6E2FC152" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having sericeous sepals while those of 
<taxonomicName id="303DFDFA7CEF1629B183601562D7A472" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abutiloides">
<emphasis id="CB8F9D5C9913EC2750C051310CE90033" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. abutiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are glabrous. The two species intergrade in the 
<normalizedToken id="09121CADECF74EA077534C733E71D7E5" originalValue="AbapÃ³">Abapo</normalizedToken>
area of Bolivia where their ranges overlap.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="36DED429881D87A29CFDEEBA306E83FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Records from Peru (Austin and Staples 1991: 273) are mostly errors for the very similar 
<taxonomicName id="8B1F19DCC7769CD2EB4D2B8DE05412C4" authority="Kuntze" authorityName="Kuntze" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pearceana">
<emphasis id="56BE6A45CEF3DA3F7223BBC20AE8D5A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea pearceana</emphasis>
Kuntze
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in little more than the relatively persistent elongate- oblong bracteoles.
</paragraph>
